\section{Munkres \S 3.24, Exercise 1}

\subsection*{(a)}

Suppose we have a homeomorphism $f : [0,1] \to (0,1)$. It is easy to
see that restriction induces a homeomorphism $[0, 1) \simeq (0,1) -
  \{f(1)\}$. But $(0,1]$ is connected and
\[
(0,1) - \{f(1)\} = (0, f(1)) \amalg (f(2), 1)
\]
is clearly disconnected, a contradiction since the continuous image of
a connected space is connected. The same argument shows that $(0,1]
  \not\simeq (0,1)$.

Finally, suppose we have a homeomorphism $g : [0, 1] \to (0,
1]$. Again, restriction induces a homeomorphism $(0, 1] \to (0, 1] -
      \{g(0)\}$. If $g(0) = 1$ this contradiction that $(0, 1]
        \not\simeq (0, 1)$, as shown above. And if $g(0) \ne 1$ the
        same connectedness argument used above gives a contradiction.

\subsection*{(b)}

Clearly we have embeddings $[0, 1] \simeq [1/3, 2/3] \subset (0, 1)$
and $(0, 1) \subset [0, 1]$, but we showed in (a) that $[0, 1]
\not\simeq (0, 1)$.

\subsection*{(c)}

Suppose we have a homeomorphism $f : \R \to \R^n$ with $n >
1$. Restriction induces a homeomorphism $\R - \{0\} \simeq \R^n -
\{f(0)\}$. But $\R - \{0\} = (-\infty, 0) \amalg (0, \infty)$ is
disconnected and clearly $\R^n - \{f(0)\}$ is (path-)connected, a
contradiction.

\begin{remark}
  This problem illustrates how to use connectedness as a way to
  distinguish between topological spaces (up to homeomorphism). But
  still, it might seem sort of dumb to you that we had to define all
  this stuff just to show $\R \not\simeq \R^n$ for $n > 1$! Shouldn't
  this be obvious? Well, let's put it this way: try to prove $\R^n
  \not\simeq \R^m$ when $n \ne m$. (Or maybe just think about it for a
  second, because it's actually hard! The point is that we need some
  higher powered ``invariants'' of topological spaces to distinguish
  between $\R^n$ and $\R^m$. And we need invariants and topological
  properties because, as you may have guessed, it's hard to just sit
  down and prove explicitly, ``it's impossible to write down a
  homeomorphism between these two spaces''.)
\end{remark}

