\section{Munkres \S 3.24, Exercise 2}

If $f(1) = f(-1)$ we're done, so assume without loss of generality
that $f(1) > f(-1)$. Consider $g : S^1 \to \R$ defined by $g(x) :=
f(x) - f(-x)$, which is continuous because addition, negation, and $f$
are continuous. By hypothesis $g(1) > 0$ and $g(-1) < 0$. Then since
$S^1$ is connected (Munkres \S 24, Example 5), by the intermediate
value theorem (Munkres, Theorem 24.3) there exists $x \in S^1$ such
that
\[
g(x) = 0 \implies f(x) = f(-x).
\]

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\section{Munkres \S 3.24, Exercise 9}

\begin{remark}
  As you will see, this is not a \textit{completely} rigorous write-up
  of the solution, and I didn't expect one, since the idea is clear
  and writing this up rigorously doesn't seem particularly appealing
  or useful.
\end{remark}

Let $x, y \in \R^2 - A$ any two distinct points. The sets of lines
$L_x \subset \R^2$ containing $x$ and $L_y \subset \R^2$ containing
$y$ are each parameterised by their slope $s \in \R$, and hence there
are uncountably many of each. As $A$ is only countable, and since a
line is uniquely determined by any two distinct points on it, there
are then uncountably many (since the union of two countable sets is
countable!) lines $L_x$ through $x$ and $L_y$ through $y$ which don't
intersect $A$. But then clearly one pair of $L_x$ and $L_y$ must
intersect, which determines a path in $\R^2 - A$ from $x$ to $y$.

